docs.abstract: Facebook’s chief executive is expected to strike a conciliatory tone about user data on Tuesday when he speaks to members of the European Parliament.
docs.snippet: Facebook’s chief executive is expected to strike a conciliatory tone about user data on Tuesday when he speaks to members of the European Parliament.
docs.lead_paragraph: SAN FRANCISCO — Mark Zuckerberg, Facebook’s chief executive, plans to strike a conciliatory note when he speaks to members of the European Parliament on Tuesday, in the latest stop on his apology tour for the social network’s mishandling of user information.

headline.main: Mark Zuckerberg to Apologize Again, This Time to European Parliament
headline.print_headline: Zuckerberg Is Set to Apologize to European Parliament

docs.abstract: Didi will acquire the rest of 99, a Brazilian ride-hailing start-up that it had invested in, in an all-cash deal worth around $600 million.
docs.snippet: Didi will acquire the rest of 99, a Brazilian ride-hailing start-up that it had invested in, in an all-cash deal worth around $600 million.
docs.lead_paragraph: RIO DE JANEIRO — Didi Chuxing, the Chinese ride-sharing company, agreed to acquire full control of 99 — the main Brazilian rival to Uber and a company in which Didi already holds a stake — for around $600 million, according to three people with knowledge of the transaction.

headline.main: Didi Chuxing, China’s Ride-Hailing Giant, Agrees to Buy Uber Rival in Brazil
headline.print_headline: Chinese Company Agrees To Buy Uber Rival in Brazil

byline.original: By Vinod Sreeharsha and Mike Isaac

docs.abstract: False claims posted on Twitter were 70 percent more likely to be shared than the truth, researchers at M.I.T. found. And people appear to prefer false news.
docs.snippet: False claims posted on Twitter were 70 percent more likely to be shared than the truth, researchers at M.I.T. found. And people appear to prefer false news.
docs.lead_paragraph: What if the scourge of false news on the internet is not the result of Russian operatives or partisan zealots or computer-controlled bots? What if the main problem is us?

headline.main: It’s True: False News Spreads Faster and Wider. And Humans Are to Blame.
headline.print_headline: Why We’re Easily Seduced by False News

docs.abstract: Would the White House run more smoothly with a new chief of staff? With a mercurial president in charge, it could well just be more of the same.
docs.snippet: Would the White House run more smoothly with a new chief of staff? With a mercurial president in charge, it could well just be more of the same.
docs.lead_paragraph: Throughout his presidential campaign Donald J. Trump extolled his business acumen and management skills, and just before his inauguration he insisted the transition to his administration was going “very, very smoothly.”

headline.main: Trump Management Style, Year 2: See Year 1
headline.print_headline: Signs Point To Another Chaotic Year Under Trump

docs.abstract: A tiff between Warren Buffett and Elon Musk reignited over the weekend. But the two do have common ground, and betting against either is risky.
docs.snippet: A tiff between Warren Buffett and Elon Musk reignited over the weekend. But the two do have common ground, and betting against either is risky.
docs.lead_paragraph: Elon Musk and Warren E. Buffett clashed over the weekend after Mr. Musk, Tesla’s chief executive, derided as lame Mr. Buffett’s concept of companies having “moats” to keep potential competitors at bay. When Mr. Buffett, the Berkshire Hathaway chairman, cited his confectionery maker, See’s Candies, as proof to the contrary, Mr. Musk pledged to launch his own candy maker. It’s an invitation for investors to take sides; many already have.

headline.main: Musk vs. Buffett: An Invitation for Investors to Take Sides

docs.abstract: An inconvenient bit of neuroscience: The more you try not to think about a bad habit, the harder it gets to resist. So think about something else.
docs.snippet: An inconvenient bit of neuroscience: The more you try not to think about a bad habit, the harder it gets to resist. So think about something else.
docs.lead_paragraph: Let’s play a little game. Clear your mind. Go ahead, clear it.

headline.main: Resistance Is Futile. To Change Habits, Try Replacement Instead.

docs.abstract: The resignation of WPP’s Martin Sorrell shocked the industry and also highlighted the question of what‘s next for advertising companies in a dynamic era.
docs.snippet: The resignation of WPP’s Martin Sorrell shocked the industry and also highlighted the question of what‘s next for advertising companies in a dynamic era.
docs.lead_paragraph: It came as a shock to Madison Avenue in the late 1980s when a British financial whiz named Martin Sorrell came for two pre-eminent American advertising agencies, embarking on hostile takeovers of J. Walter Thompson and the Ogilvy Group on his way to forging a global empire.

headline.main: Prominent Exit From Ad Industry Sets Off Questions About Future
headline.print_headline: Prominent Exit Spurs Questions About Future

docs.abstract: The chief executive had initially resisted meeting with European authorities, who have emerged as the world’s most assertive watchdog of the technology industry.
docs.snippet: The chief executive had initially resisted meeting with European authorities, who have emerged as the world’s most assertive watchdog of the technology industry.
docs.lead_paragraph: European lawmakers barraged Facebook’s chief executive, Mark Zuckerberg, on Tuesday with a litany of questions about his company’s global power, its role in elections and its misuse of user data. One even raised the prospect of breaking up the social media giant.

headline.main: Facebook’s Mark Zuckerberg Gets an Earful From the E.U.
headline.print_headline: Zuckerberg Faces European Officials’ Questioning. Few Leave Satisfied.

docs.abstract: Rowan University and the Borough of Glassboro overcame years of distrust to revitalize the downtown area with retail, restaurants and student housing.
docs.snippet: Rowan University and the Borough of Glassboro overcame years of distrust to revitalize the downtown area with retail, restaurants and student housing.
docs.lead_paragraph: GLASSBORO, N.J. — Joseph A. Brigandi Jr. remembers when his father ran a sub shop in the heart of this southern New Jersey town in the 1960s, when there were only four or five restaurants downtown and no out-of-town shopping malls threatened the survival of local businesses.

headline.main: New Jersey Town and University Bridge Their Divide, and Both Reap a Reward
headline.print_headline: A College Town That Works, for the College and the Town

docs.abstract: Tapper’s debut novel, “The Hellfire Club,” a historical thriller set in 1950s Washington, has some unsettling parallels to today’s political climate.
docs.snippet: Tapper’s debut novel, “The Hellfire Club,” a historical thriller set in 1950s Washington, has some unsettling parallels to today’s political climate.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Jake Tapper doesn’t seem to get rattled easily. He’s got a TV anchor’s unflappable poise and immovable hair, and radiates an almost eerie calm when a dozen explosive stories break during his daily CNN show. He’s weathered relentless online attacks from the right for his interrogations of Trump administration officials, and seemed unruffled when the president attacked him as a “CNN flunky” on Twitter. (Mr. Tapper retweeted the message, with an eye-roll emoji.)

headline.main: CNN’s Jake Tapper Has Emerged as a Staunch Defender of Facts in the Trump Era. So Why Is He Writing Fiction?
headline.print_headline: The Parallels in Jake Tapper’s New Novel
